ting 6 k from both sides of this equation yields 13 equals 2 k minus 29. Adding 29 to both sides of this equation yields 42 equals 2 k, or 2 k equals 42. Dividing both sides of this equation by 2 yields k equals 21. It''s given that lines m and n are parallel, and the figure shows that lines m and n are intersected by a transversal, line t. If two parallel lines are intersected by a transversal, then the same-side interior angles are supplementary. It follows that the same-side interior angles with measures y degree and z degree are supplementary, so y plus z equals 180. Substituting 8 k minus 29 for y in this equation yields 8 k minus 29 plus z equals 180. Substituting 21 for k in this equation yields 8 left parenthesis 21 right parenthesis minus 29 plus z equals 180, or 139 plus z equals 180. Subtracting 139 from both sides of this equation yields z equals 41. Therefore, the value of z is 41.\nChoice A is incorrect and may result from conceptual or calculation errors.\nChoice B is incorrect. This is the value of k, not z.\nChoice D is incorrect. This is the value of x or y, not z."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-236", "text": "For a certain rectangular region, the ratio of its length to its width is 35 to 10. If the width of the rectangular region increases by 7 units, how must the length change to maintain this ratio?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["It must decrease by 24.5 units.", "It must increase by 24.5 units.", "It must decrease by 7 units.", "It must increase by 7 units."], "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "normal", "explanation": "Choice B is correct. It\u2019s given that the ratio of the rectangular region\u2019s length to its width is 35 to 10. This can be written as a proportion: StartFraction length Over width EndFraction equals StartFraction 35 Over 10 EndFraction, or StartFraction script l Over w EndFraction equals StartFraction 35 Over 10 EndFraction. This proportion can be rewritten as 10 script l equals 35 w, or script l equals 3.5 w. If the width of the rectangular region increases by 7, then the length will increase by some number x in order to maintain this ratio. The value of x can be found by replacing script l with script l plus x and w with w plus 7 in the equation, which gives script l plus x equals 3.5 left parenthesis w plus 7 right parenthesis. This equation can be rewritten using the distributive property as script l plus x equals 3.5 w plus 24.5. Since script l equals 3.5 w, the right-hand side of this equation can be rewritten by substituting script l for 3.5 w, which gives script l plus x equals script l plus 24.5, or x equals 24.5. Therefore, if the width of the rectangular region increases by 7 units, the length must increase by 24.5 units in order to maintain the given ratio.\nChoice A is incorrect. If the width of the rectangular region increases, the length must also increase, not decrease.\nChoice C is incorrect. If the width of the rectangular region increases, the length must also increase, not decrease.\nChoice D is incorrect. Since the ratio of the length to the width of the rectangular region is 35 to 10, if the width of the rectangular region increases by 7 units, the length would have to increase by a proportional amount, which would have to be greater than 7 units."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-239", "text": "A cylinder has a diameter of 8 inches and a height of 12 inches. What is the volume, in cubic inches, of the cylinder?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["16 pi", "96 pi", "192 pi", "768 pi"], "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "normal", "explanation": "Choice C is correct. The base of a cylinder is a circle with a diameter equal to the diameter of the cylinder. The volume, upper V, of a cylinder can be found by multiplying the area of the circular base, upper A, by the height of the cylinder, h, or upper V equals upper A h. The area of a circle can be found using the formula upper A equals pi r squared, where r is the radius of the circle. It\u2019s given that the diameter of the cylinder is 8 inches. Thus, the radius of this circle is 4 inches. Therefore, the area of the circular base of the cylinder is upper A equals pi left parenthesis 4 right parenthesis squared, or 16 pi square inches. It\u2019s given that the height h of the cylinder is 12 inches. Substituting 16 pi for upper A and 12 for h in the formula upper V equals upper A h gives upper V equals 16 pi left parenthesis 12 right parenthesis, or 192 pi cubic inches.\nChoice A is incorrect. This is the area of the circular base of the cylinder.\nChoice B is incorrect and may result from using 8, instead of 16, as the value of r squared in the formula for the area of a circle.\nChoice D is incorrect and may result from using 8, instead of 4, for the radius of the circular base."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-242", "text": "g left parenthesis x right parenthesis equals x squared plus 55\nWhat is the minimum value of the given function?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["0", "55", "110", "3,025"], "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "normal", "explanation": "Choice B is correct. For a quadratic function defined by an equation of the form g left parenthesis x right parenthesis equals a left parenthesis x minus h right parenthesis squared plus k, where a, h, and k are constants and a greater than 0, the minimum value of the function is k. In the given function, a equals 1, h equals 0, and k equals 55. Therefore, the minimum value of the given function is 55.\nChoice A is incorrect. This is the value of x for which the given function reaches its minimum value, not the minimum value of the function.\nChoice C is incorrect and may result from conceptual or calculation errors.\nChoice D is incorrect and may result from conceptual or calculation errors."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-246", "text": "Right triangles upper L upper M upper N and upper P upper Q upper